Quintilian (i 9) tells us that Asinius Pollio, the celebrated orator, historiari, and poet of the Augustan age, reproached Livy with Patavinitas—that is, a provincial mode of expression in use at Patavium, as distinguished from the standard style of the capital. It is vain for us now to inquire in what this consisted; for though we may be able to state the difference between the style of one author and that of another, we are not in a position to recognise slight dialectic varieties, perhaps merely of pronunciation. Besides, Asinius Pollio, having rather too high an idea of his own abitinas, was considerably addicted to speaking slightingly of other distin- guished authors. Quintilian informs us (xii. 1. ᾗ 22) that he even ventured to depreciate Cicero's style. The Patavinity‚ therefore, tnay be nothing but a petty spiteful invention.
